ANTHRAX, GLOBAL BACKGROUND ACTIVITY (02)
****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Anthrax, global background activity: RFI 980331000425
Date: Tue, 31 Mar 1998 10:00:34 +0000
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following data on anthrax in five additional countries
were extracted from the GIDEON software program:
Portugal:
189 cases were reported during 1965 to 1973; 66 during 1974
to 1981; 6 in 1990; 1 in 1991; 3 in 1992; 4 in 1993; 5 in
1994; 2 in 1995; 5 in 1996. Beja accounted for 12 of 21
cases reported during 1990 to 1995.
Spain:
2,685 cases were reported during 1965 to 1973; 1,996 during
1974 to 1981; 81 in 1992; 79 in 1993 (77.21% from
Castilla la Mancha, Castilla Leon and Aragon); 82 in 1994;
64 in 1995 (80% from Castilla la Mancha, Aragon, Castilla
Leon and Extremadura); 50 in 1996.
South Africa:
0 to 3 animal outbreaks are reported annually. The largest
epizootic was recorded in 1923 - 30,000 to 60,000 animals
died of the disease. The peak reporting years were 1921 (110
cases), and 1938 (110 cases). No human cases were reported
in 1993; 0 in 1994; 3 (nonfatal) in 1995; 1 (nonfatal) in
1996.
United Kingdom:
97 cases were reported during 1965 to 1973 (65 from England
and Wales, 3 Northern Ireland, 29 Scotland); 25 during
1974 to 1979 (19 England and Wales, 0 Northern Ireland, 6
Scotland). Scotland reported 1 case in 1990 and 1 in
1992. A cattle outbreak was reported in Gloucestershire in
1994 (cattle infection is also suspected on the Isle of
Wight). One human case was reported in Northern Ireland in
1993, and one in England in 1995.
Haiti:
27% to 50% of goatskin products (drums, voodoo dolls, rugs)
are contaminated. 1,587 cases of human anthrax were
reported from the southern peninsula during 1973 to 1977; 85
cases in 1983; 1,396 cases and 5 deaths during 1985 to
1988. 164 cases were reported in the Commune of Jeremie in
1988. Over 100 cases (> 12 deaths) were reported in La
Brillere in 1993.
--
Dr. Steve Berger
